    <div class="story-body">
      <p class="body-text">Wall covering. A hockey stick. Blood pressure meters. What do these three items have in common? They were all lost on New York City public transportation, according to an MTA dataset that lists every catalogued lost item. </p>
      <p class="body-text">The MTA is the largest public transportation agency in North America and encompasses all subways and buses for the five boroughs. MTA's New York City Transit Lost and Found Office is in charge of the dataset and holds items for three months to three years, depending on the circumstance. They have successfully returned 90,632 items back to its owners.</p>
      <p class="body-text">And while some types of lost categories are predictable -- like wallets, ID's, or cell phones, there are some categories no one would expect, such as musical instruments and transit equipment lost by MTA employees.</p>
      <p class="body-text"></p>
