      <p class="body-text">Identification items alone make up about 220,000 lost items -- that's about 79 percent of the total amount of objects lost. It's also more than twice the amount of lost items that were claimed or returned to its rightful owners.</p> </div>

    {{> story/lost_items }}
      
              <br><div class="story-body">
         <p class="body-text">When asked about this dataset, which is a <a href='http://advisory.mtanyct.info/LPUWebServices/CurrentLostProperty.aspx'>hidden HTML-only page</a> on the MTA website, a representative for the NYCT Lost and Found Office would not comment on the last time it was updated or if it's an accurate count (an inquiry was officially opened and is pending).</p>
      <p class="body-text">If you lose your belongings on New York City public transit, you can file a claim on the MTA website and check the NYCT Lost and Found Office located at 34 St-Penn Station.</p>
      <p class="body-text">And remember: always check to make sure you have everything before you leave the subway car or bus.</p>
